Getting the past years of Stock data from Alpha Vantage¶

You can use the below code to get the Financial statements (Income, Balance, Cash Flow) for the various companies you are interested in if you are willing to pay for the premium service.

In [ ]:
import requests
import json

#alpha_vantage_api_key = <You can get a free key from Alpha Vantage>

#For premium accounts, you can follow below code to make multiple api calls across multiple stocks
#We wish to extract the income statement, the balance sheets, and the statement of cash flow
financial_statements = ["INCOME_STATEMENT", "BALANCE_SHEET", "CASH_FLOW"]
stocks = ["APPL", "META"]

urls_list = ["https://www.alphavantage.co/query?function="+ statement + "&symbol="+ ticker + "&apikey="+ alpha_vantage_api_key for ticker in stocks for statement in financial_statements]
data = [requests.get(url).json() for url in urls_list]

#formattd_json so that it is in an easier format to read
formatted_json = json.dumps(data, indent=4)

print(formatted_json)

Otherwise, do note that for their free service, there is a limit on the number of API calls you can make within certain time periods. As such, if you are using the free service, I suggest using the code below and zoning in on certain parts of the Financial Statements you are interested in for a particular stock.

In [ ]:
import requests
import json

#alpha_vantage_api_key = <You can get a free key from Alpha Vantage>

financial_statements = "INCOME_STATEMENT"
stocks = "AAPL"

url_income_statement = "https://www.alphavantage.co/query?function="+ financial_statements + "&symbol="+ stocks + "&apikey="+ alpha_vantage_api_key
requests_json_income_statement = requests.get(url_income_statement).json()

#formattd_json so that it is in an easier format to read
data_income_statement = json.dumps(requests_json_income_statement, indent=4)

print(data_income_statement)

#convert the list into a pandas dataframe

import pandas as pd
df_income_statement = pd.DataFrame(quarterly_income, columns = ["fiscalDateEnding",
                                                                "netIncome",
                                                                "grossProfit",
                                                                "totalRevenue",
                                                                "costofGoodsAndServicesSold",
                                                                "operatingIncome",
                                                                "sellingGeneralAndAdministrative",
                                                                "researchAndDevelopment",
                                                                "operatingExpenses",
                                                                "interestExpense",
                                                                "depreciation",
                                                                "incomeBeforeTax"])

# Sort the DataFrame by the fiscalDateEnding column
df_sorted_income_statement = df_income_statement.sort_values(by="fiscalDateEnding")

#Currently python is viewing the values as string; hence need to convert values to integers
columns_to_convert = ["netIncome",
                      "grossProfit",
                      "totalRevenue",
                      "costofGoodsAndServicesSold",
                      "operatingIncome",
                      "sellingGeneralAndAdministrative",
                      "researchAndDevelopment",
                      "operatingExpenses",
                      "interestExpense",
                      "depreciation",
                      "incomeBeforeTax"]#,
                      #"grossProfitMargin"]

#In case of nan values, fill it as integer 0
for col in columns_to_convert:
    df_sorted_income_statement[col] = pd.to_numeric(df_sorted_income_statement[col], errors='coerce').fillna(0).astype(int)

For a company to have sustained competive advantage, gross profit margins (>40%) and net income should be in a steady uptrend over a prolonged period.¶

In [ ]:
#We create our own metric grossProfitMargin
df_sorted_income_statement["grossProfitMargin"] = df_sorted_income_statement["grossProfit"] / df_sorted_income_statement["totalRevenue"]

import matplotlib. pyplot as plt

plt.plot(df_sorted_income_statement["fiscalDateEnding"], df_sorted_income_statement["grossProfit"] / df_sorted_income_statement["totalRevenue"], marker='o', linestyle='-', color='g', label='grossProfitMargin')
# Set y-axis label to indicate millions
plt.ylabel("Gross Profit Margin")

plt.xlabel("Fiscal Date Ending")
plt.title("Gross Profit Margins Over Time")
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.legend()  # Show legend with labels
plt.tight_layout()

# Show the graph
plt.show()

msft.info

msft.actions

msft.dividends

msft.splits

msft.major_holders

msft.cashflow
msft.quarterly_cashflow

msft.earnings_dates

msft.isin

msft.options

        try:
            source.extend([stock, stock_info['sector'], stock_info['totalRevenue'], stock_info['currentRatio'],stock_info['earningsGrowth'],stock_info['trailingPE']])

            continue
    return source

import yfinance as yf
import pendulum
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

stock = input("What stock are you interested in? \n Please enter a valid Stock Ticker Symbol such as TSLA for Tesla")
period = input("Over what historical time period are you interested in? \n You may enter one of the following periods: 1d, 5d, 1mo, 3mo, 6mo, 1y, 2y, 5y, 10y, ytd, max")
interval = input("What is the interval you would like to see between each stock price? \n You may enter one of the following: 1m,2m,5m,15m,30m,60m,90m,1h,1d,5d,1wk,1mo,3mo")
measure = input("Which price aspect are you interested in? \n You may enter one of the following: 'Open', 'High', 'Low', 'Close', 'Volume', 'Dividends', 'Stock Splits'")
#price_history.columns.values

price_history = yf.Ticker(stock).history(period=period, interval=interval)
#valid periods: 1d, 5d, 1mo, 3mo, 6mo, 1y, 2y, 5y, 10y, ytd, max
#valid intervals: #1m,2m,5m,15m,30m,60m,90m,1h,1d,5d,1wk,1mo,3mo
time_series = list(price_history[measure])
#dt_list=[pendulum.parse(str(dt)).float_timestamp for dt in list(price_history.index)]
dt_list=[pendulum.parse(str(dt)) for dt in list(price_history.index)]
#plt.style.use('dark_background')

#x axis
plt.xlabel('Period')
plt.xticks(rotation=90)

#y axis
plt.ylabel(measure)

# displaying the title
plt.title(label= (measure, "over Historical Period of", period), fontsize=13, color="white")

#print visualisation
plt.plot(dt_list,time_series,linewidth=2)
